<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-205-122 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 439 258</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  March 4 1991 n341 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New age of E-mail: combos with LAN applications. (local areanetwork, electronic mail)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jackson, Kelly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Users of local area networks are bombarded with electronic mailmessages.andP;  The glut worsens as the number of electronic mail usersincreases.andP;  Users must have ways to separate 'junk' E-mail fromurgent messages and blend E-mail with other network applications.andO;A new age for electronic messaging is necessary where the mediumand the message are unique and cooperation and consolidation amongvendors is a must.andP;  E-mail software is now available that willautomate desktop applications and an organization's businessmethods.andP;  Two factors influence the next generation of LAN E-mail.andO;One is the move away from proprietary E-mail programs toward opensystems.andP;  The other is the splitting of E-mail software into twodirections: a message transport vehicle and front-end userapplications.andP;  The more connections an applications has with itscompetitors, the better.andP;  Separate and proprietary E-mail systemsare out.andP;  Vendors have developed applications programminginterfaces for users and developers to create new connections withtheir software.andP;  Industry observers say vendors like Apple andNovell plan to include E-mail in network operating systems at nocharge.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (Product development)Novell Inc. (Product development).andO;Topic:     Electronic Mail SystemsLocal Area NetworksProduct DevelopmentApplications Programming InterfaceOpen Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>